<HEAD>Tropical Storm Ernesto Fizzles En Route To Azores</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Changes overline and LEADS with 5 grafs to update with storm
fizzling, latest advisory; picks up 6th graf pvs, `The storm...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fifth tropical storm of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season lost its strength as it raced towards <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Azores </LOCATION> island chain, and its remnants were absorbed by a large north <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> storm system Sunday. Tropical Storm Ernesto, located roughly 400 miles north of the <LOCATION> Azores </LOCATION> near latitude 45.0 north at longitude 28.0 west, could no longer be identified late Sunday, according to a 10:30 p.m. advisory from the National Hurricane Center. Earlier in the evening, the storm had top sustained winds of 40 mph and was racing northeastward toward the <LOCATION> Azores </LOCATION> at about 50 mph. The <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> on the islands monitored the storm but chose to not warn residents Sunday evening, said <ORGANIZATION> Azores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Baiao </PERSON>. Meteorologist <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> of the Hurricane Center said <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> probably would lose strength when it moved over colder water. `` The storm draws its strength from the warm, moist tropical water,'' he said. `` Even a few degrees can affect the storm.'' Tropical storms have wind of at least 39 mph rotating around a warm core of low pressure. If sustained wind reaches 74 mph, the system is upgraded to a hurricane. If wind drops below 39 mph, it is downgraded to a tropical depression. On Saturday, storm warnings for the Gulf coast from <LOCATION> Cameron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Apalachicola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, were canceled after a tropical depression dissipated several hours after forming off the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> coast. The first hurricane of the season, <PERSON> Debby </PERSON>, swirled to life Friday but was downgraded to a tropical storm hours later after moving inland at <LOCATION> Tuxpan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, about 165 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season runs from June 1 to Nov. 30.
