<HEAD>Forecasters Say Hurricane Winds No Longer Pose Threat to Hawaii</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tropical storm watch for the Hawaiian islands was discontinued but high surf advisories were in effect as Hurricane Uleki moved away from the state, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. At 2 p.m. Sunday, or 8 p.m. EDT, the hurricane was 385 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> and 350 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Lihue </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kauai </LOCATION>, moving to the west at 12 mph with maximum sustained winds of 80 mph and gusts to 100 mph, meteorologist <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Uleki </PERSON>'s westward movement lessened the threat of damaging winds for <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> is located, <LOCATION> Kauai </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Niihau </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. However, a high surf advisory remained in effect for all southern coasts that were pounded by large waves from the storm. Rescuers assisted 19 people Saturday in 5 - to 6-foot waves off <LOCATION> Waikiki </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and nearby <LOCATION> Ala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, according to lifeguard Capt <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>. A body was discovered Sunday off <LOCATION> Maunalua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> eight miles east of <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, but it was not immediately known if the death was related to the storm, police said. <PERSON> Uleki </PERSON> was expected to continue moving westward, and gradually weaken to the point where it could be downgraded from hurricane status this afternoon, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. When the storm took an unexpected turn toward the islands Friday, winds near the center gusted to 150 mph. Uleki is Hawaiian for <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON>. The weather service in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> said the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> region has its own list of Hawaiian names for storms in the region. Next will be <PERSON> Wila </PERSON>, followed by <LOCATION> Aka </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ekeka </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hale </PERSON>. So few storms originate in the region that the list is used over and over, and does not start the year with a name beginning with the letter A as in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> or other regions of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>.
