. The rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> took up arms against the government in 1983 and claims control over 90 percent of the southern countryside and towns. Fierce fighting between the government and rebels has forced southerners to leave crops and cattle for the safety of towns. Faced with dwindling food and medical supplies in these towns, southerners often try to make their way farther north, usually on foot. Another report reaching the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> said the situation in <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION> `` is dramatically deteriorating.'' It said floods washed away roads and bridges connecting the town with the outside, blocking whatever relief supplies might get through. The report said food supplies, especially southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s staple sorghum, are low in <LOCATION> Wau </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION>, the south's main city 750 miles south of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> The report said floods caused by heavy rains and fighting in the area was obstructing Western relief organizations' efforts to bring food and medicine to these areas.
