<HEAD>Presidential Game Well Under Way at Labor Day Kickoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> make campaign-launching Labor Day appearances Monday in a race for the presidency that has ignored the ceremonial starting point and is already a close and caustic contest. `` It kicked off earlier than any presidential campaign I've ever seen,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Greer </PERSON>, a consultant to Democratic candidates. `` The intensity this early is really astounding.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic nominee who has seen a huge midsummer's lead evaporate, campaigns through the industrial <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> hungering for the elusive intangibles of momentum and initiative that he once commanded <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the vice president and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nominee, enters the final nine weeks of his race for the White House appearing in control of their long-distance debate, at least for now, and enjoying a resurrection in the polls. He was campaigning on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> communications director <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dach </PERSON> said Labor Day is `` when the season really starts'' and represents the point where the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor steps up his pace from three days of campaign travel to five each week. But the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign was making no effort to cloak its candidate in the traditions of Labor Day. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> passed up a chance for a visual send-off before the Statue of Liberty, where <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> began his fall campaign in 1980, and a symbolic appearance with his running mate. `` Labor Day as an opening day has been overtaken by events,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON>. Those events include a blistering round of attacks on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> leveled by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> immediately after the Democrats spent four July days ridiculing the vice president at their <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> convention. And, they include the debate over <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s controversial running mate, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, whose selection at a minimum forced a vacationing electorate to notice this presidential race. Both campaigns have revealed their themes, too. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is focusing on the economy, and middle class unease about the economic future, as well as questioning the judgment and fitness of the Republican ticket. `` Most Americans do n't feel they're sharing in <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s prosperity,'' said <PERSON> Dach </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spokesman `` We're going to run on the economic issues. Those are the issues that are going to decide this election. What <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is trying to do is deflect the debate off the issues that people really care about.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has concentrated on raising doubts about <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his record as governor, while suggesting gentle change from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in such areas as protecting the environment. Now <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plans to focus on jobs and the economy. Still to come are what may be the main events: televised debates, where an error can wreck a candidacy; and the wars of television advertising, which are certain to be hard fought. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s TV ads will begin airing soon, campaign manager <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> said. Media adviser <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailes </PERSON> is not tipping his hand on the content, but campaign sources said among them may be one featuring <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> victims terrorized by convicted murderer <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, who escaped while on a furlough from the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> prison system. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has made a major campaign issue of the furlough program that allowed passes for first-degree murderers, and which <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> reluctantly agreed to amend in the face of public outcry. Confident of his debating style honed as a public television show host, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is eager to confront <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign, however, has attempted to minimize the debates. It has agreed to two debates, plus a third between the running mates, and is insisting on scheduling them in late September and early October _ when the Olympics and World Series may keep some viewers away. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> responded strongly to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during their summer jousting, even at one point evoking the imagery of rotting fish heads in describing President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his vice president. But his campaign clearly is frustrated by the appearance that he is reacting and on the defensive, unable to direct the debate. There was implicit admission that all is not well in <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' announcement Friday of the return of his former campaign manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>, who resigned in controversy a year earlier And <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on occasion has seemed tentative and reluctant in their long-distance debates, some believe. `` I'm not sure the Democrats have given back as good as we got,'' said <PERSON> Greer </PERSON>. `` I think we were lulled by that large lead.'' Where he once led by double-digit margins, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was shown in a dead heat with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> according to most recent polls, including an <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> poll last week. It had <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> up by 1 percentage point, 43-42, statistically insignificant. `` I do n't think anyone in the campaign, from top to bottom, anticipated the race tightening up to our advantage this quick,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> manager <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>. `` Our key is not to get confident, not to get cocky about it.'' Some Republicans believe <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> still trails a bit, however. `` I would say we're still realistically 5-6-7 points down,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> consultant <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahe </PERSON>, who is doing work for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. He bases that on the difference, in some polls, of respondents who say they are deeply committed to a candidate. The battle is largely for those wavering or swing voters. They are often described as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Democrats, self-identified independents or Democrats who turned away from the party in 1980 and 1984. But what is striking is that the race is breathtakingly close all across the nation _ including the big battleground states like <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Even <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>'s home state of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> is even or nearly so in a recent poll. `` When <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was ahead, he was ahead everywhere. When <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> took the lead, it was everywhere. When it evens out now, it's kind of even everywhere,'' said <PERSON> Greer </PERSON>. `` It's amazing.''
