<FIRST>r w AM-US-Salvador Bjt   09-04 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Salvador, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: U.S. Aid Failed to Cure Social, Economic Ills in El
Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid has helped prevent the takeover of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> by leftist guerrillas but has failed to solve the underlying social problems that sparked the insurgency, say four <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> lieutenant colonels who have served in the Central American nation and in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. `` The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> foundation for conducting small wars is defective,'' said the report, prepared while the four officers were on fellowships at the <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. The unsatisfactory results of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, which the authors described as neither victory nor defeat, stem in part from local conditions and in part from the failure of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to clearly define its goals, they said. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> provided resources not on the basis of some overall vision of success but in response to successive and increasingly acute crises,'' said the four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers, Lt. Cols. A.J. <PERSON> Bacevich </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hallums </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. Administration officials failed to formulate a long-term strategy to help cure the social and economic ills of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, and did not coordinate the efforts of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military and civilian advisers, said the report. The report also concluded that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military, despite the lessons of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, helped mold the Salvadoran armed forces into a organization better suited for big European-style conflicts than Third World guerrilla wars. Their findings were contained in a 58-page booklet published by the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analysis </ORGANIZATION>, affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> Fletcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> on Law and Diplomacy at <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> Medford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. `` As long as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> remains a great power, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> involvement in small wars will recur with some frequency,'' they wrote. `` To find fault with American military policy in a particular instance is not to suggest that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is incapable of effective assistance to an ally threatened by an insurgency. The important thing is to get it right,'' they wrote, offering the following suggestions: _ `` Make room for the study of small wars in military schools.'' _ `` Clarify organizational responsibilities for fighting small wars, in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and in the field.'' _ `` Before undertaking any intervention, establish a vision of what you hope to accomplish and a consensus of political support to sustain that vision.'' _ `` Send your first team and permit its members the latitude to get the job done'' rather than training all capable officers to fight only large-scale wars. _ `` Avoid introducing inappropriate technology.'' The lieutenant colonels questioned other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers with experience in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and found that none of them `` viewed the Salvadoran insurgency as primarily a military problem.'' `` None believed that killing guerrillas alone would win the war. All expressed the belief that only through political, social and economic reform could the Salvadoran government hope to defeat the insurgency,'' the report said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort was also hampered by unreliable `` baloney-slice funding'' doled out by an unenthusiastic <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the report said. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> Salvadoran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> have been molded along the lines of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military, which is better suited to major ground offensives than to small-unit guerrilla fighting. `` Almost instinctively, Americans take a rich man's approach to war,'' the report said. `` They view <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> access to technology, however expensive, as offering a significant comparative advantage over potential adversaries,'' it said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military advisers have imbued Salvadoran officers with the same outlook, the report said. `` Take the example of artillery. The Salvadoran Army fields 54 105 mm howitzers, employing them in one or two gun sections used primarily for harassing and interdiction.'' `` American experience in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> demonstrated that harassing and interdiction fires in an insurgency are at best wasteful and at worst counterproductive.'' Nonetheless, the report said, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> advisers endorsed the request of the Salvadoran military `` to replace its current howitzers with a new model that is identical in caliber but air-transportable.'' Similarly, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military backed a <LOCATION> Salvadoran </LOCATION> request for more sophisticated fighters and helicopters, although `` scarcely a week goes by without an aircraft being destroyed or damaged in an incident stemming from questionable maintenance or dubious flying skills'' by Salvadorans inadequately trained to handle super-sophisticated gadgetry. Moreover, guerrilla forces in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> are no longer capable of fighting major engagements, in which sophisticated fighters and helicopters can help, and `` now operate in smaller units and emphasize hit-and-run attacks'' in which such air support is of limited use, the authors wrote.
