<HEAD>Drought Claims Trout In Pristine Sierra River</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs first graf to insert dropped word `self-sustaining.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The release of silty water from the bottom of a reservoir to irrigate alfalfa has killed hundreds of fish in one of the last self-sustaining trout streams in the West, authorities said. The release turned a nine-mile stretch of the once-pristine <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Walker </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in the eastern <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> into a silt-choked brown wash. Some of the trout asphyxiated when silt clogged their gills were almost 2 feet long and weighed more than 9 pounds. The river was declared dead by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Trout, a 3,400-member sportsmen's conservation group that opposed the water release. `` The reservoir release has successfully killed all the trout'' in the river, said spokesman <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockel </PERSON>, who called the loss `` catastrophic.'' The water _ the lower 12 feet of the <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reservoir </LOCATION> _ was released on Wednesday and Thursday for farmers and ranchers downstream near <LOCATION> Yerington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev </LOCATION>. Farmers and ranchers said they needed the water and had a legal right to it. They said they're struggling after two straight dry winters and that the water might save this year's crop of alfalfa, used as livestock feed. The East Walker, 110 miles south of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, was one of the eastern <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION>'s last trophy trout streams. It did not need to be stocked, having one of the few self-sustaining wild trout populations in the West. `` All these dead fish, it sends a chill up my spine,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Markwith </PERSON>, a fly fisherman from <LOCATION> Redwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` We'll find some place else to fish this weekend, but it wo n't be as good.'' In August, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Trout unsuccessfully tried to obtain a restraining order against the draining of the reservoir. `` We have no problems sharing this water with our neighbors in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> _ they have a problem, too,'' <PERSON> Rockel </PERSON> said. `` But we have a problem of losing our fishery and it looks like we did, all because of improper management.''
