<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The communist government has approved a new group that advocates multiparty elections, but members say they have no intention of starting their own political party. The Hungarian Democratic Forum established itself as a `` democratic, intellectual and political movement'' by adopting a charter on Saturday, the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> reported. Hungarian state radio said the forum wants to field candidates for national, regional and local elections. But forum members said they do n't plan to form a political party and only want to promote `` an open coalition-type movement, open to any honest thoughts and initiatives.'' The forum's 364 delegates met in a tent at <LOCATION> Lakitelek </LOCATION>, 75 miles south of <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, the same village where a group of nonconformist intellectuals met in September 1987 to form a loose organization under the same name. Commenting on the forum meeting, government spokesman <PERSON> Gyoergy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marosan </PERSON> told Hungarian radio, `` On the basis of government policy, this is a welcome development.'' <PERSON> Marosan </PERSON>, the son of a former leading Social Democrat in pre-communist <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, said the government would cooperate with the movement as long as the forum cooperates. He said if people wonder about the `` foundation of a new party,'' they underestimate recent changes in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Prime Minister <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, who took over from <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> in May, has pushed for political and economic reforms. <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> had led <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> since Soviet troops put down the Hungarian uprising in 1956. The fact that the meeting was reported in the state media was another indication that the forum has received official blessing. <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> said the forum considers a multiparty system `` indispens