egative ads are coming from the Democratic and Republican national committees, which are running multimillion dollar generic media campaigns designed to promote party themes and accomplishments as superior to the opposition. The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> just completed a $ 4 million TV ad campaign that involved three spots running for two weeks in every state. The ads claim Americans have known only peace and prosperity under Republicans, so why change? <ORGANIZATION> RNC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Brainard </PERSON> said plans for the timing and content of next wave were up in the air but `` things are in place'' for another hit if it is needed. `` We're going to wait and see the tenor of the campaign,'' she said. `` There may be a need to issue specific ads of some kind that incorporate our message of peace, prosperity, economic growth and seven years of success.'' The <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION>, financially equipped to run its first major generic campaign this year, bought $ 75,000 worth of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> airtime for a quick counterpunch to the initial <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> ads and this week embarks on a $ 1 million-plus generic ad campaign in seven to 12 swing states likely to include <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION> ads, centered on the theme of `` bringing prosperity home,'' are two-pronged. Some deal with competitiveness, world debt and the deficit _ making <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> No. 1 again. Others talk about economics on a more personal scale _ health care, child care, the ability to buy homes and cars. The point, said <PERSON> Dach </PERSON>, is that `` if you're a family that's working harder to stay in place, you ca n't afford to vote Republican. By the time the Bush-Dukakis campaign ends, <PERSON> Jamieson </PERSON> said, negative TV advertising should surpass the high-water mark set during the bitter 1964 Johnson-Goldwater battle, the most negative to date. Observers cite a number of factors in explaining why they expect a nasty TV campaign: _ Attack ads were a major feature of both party's primary contests this year, providing both precedent and raw material _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and to some extent <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> are already giving very tough speeches, and advertising traditionally is more negative than speeches _ The candidates are neck-and-neck in the polls, giving them both an incentive to go negative _ Neither candidate is particularly well-defined, making it imperative that every attack be answered by a counter-attack lest voters get and keep the wrong idea _ Both candidates are relatively centrist, with few significant differences on issues `` If you do n't have broad issue disagreements, then you concentrate on the personal,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> professor specializing in election media, polling and direct mail. <PERSON> Jamieson </PERSON> said the 1964 campaign was the most negative in the number of negative ads produced and aired, but neither candidate devoted more than one-third of his air time to negative ads. She and <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON> predicted negative messages will fill one-third to one-half of each candidate's air time this year, and neither will let negative ads eclipse positive ones. Why? `` It's just too risky in terms of backlash,'' <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON> said. `` Attacking is not presidential,'' added <PERSON> Jamieson </PERSON>. `` You can get by with negative ads as long as the positive message is out there.''
