<HEAD>Two Visions of Vermont Collide in Debate Over Barn Construction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRAFTSBURY COMMON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two visions of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> have collided in this picturesque hilltop village of austere white buildings and a village green. One has to do with polished antiques, fine food and weekends of leisure in the countryside; the other has to do with morning chores, rutted pastures and muddy shoes. The dispute is being aired in hearing rooms and involves an effort by a small college here to build a genuine livestock barn within sight of the manicured English gardens of the Inn on the Common, with its croquet lawn, clay tennis court and Adirondack chairs from which guests take in the panoramic view. `` People come here for peace and quiet. They do n't come here to be put in the middle of a farm yard,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON>, who with his wife, <PERSON> Penny </PERSON>, opened the inn 14 years ago after leaving their jobs in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in investment banking and advertising. Students at <ORGANIZATION> Sterling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, a 75-student school offering programs in farming and forestry served up with a back-to-the-land ethic, are erecting a barn whose rafters can be seen from the Inn's garden The Schmitts' opposition to the barn and a second one planned nearby was dismissed recently by the District 7 <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johnsbury </LOCATION>. But they have appealed to the state <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON> said the barn violates the artistic intent of the inn, whose gardens were built in the 1930s and are part of a historic district on the National Register of Historic Places. `` The idea is to create not just pretty flower clumps but to create a total outdoor room, if you will,'' she said. `` We are not anti-farming,'' she said. `` This is not a farm versus tourism issue. Tourism and farming are bound together in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>. People come to <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> to look at the beautiful farms and fields.'' A <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> view can contain barns, she said, `` but you do what is appropriate where you find it.'' Construction permits are granted in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> under a 1970 development control law written to preserve the state's rural character. A District 7 commission member said this is the first time in his memory that the law has been used to oppose construction of barns. Sterling College President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowen </PERSON> said the school needs the barns to continue its agricultural programs. `` We have tried to do this with the least negative impact as possible on our neighbors,'' he said. In its ruling, the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> dismissed the Schmitts' concerns about barnyard noises, smells and insects wafting over a fence and onto their property The barn is about 800 feet from the inn. `` Although animals may occasionally be heard at the Inn and at area residences, this noise will be similar to the sounds produced by other farming operations in the area,'' the commission wrote. Legally, construction can go on during the Schmitts' appeal to the state <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. But the college is proceeding at its own risk. On the issue of aesthetics, the commission applied a test in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> law that bars projects having an `` undue adverse impact.'' It found that while the impact of the barns would be adverse, it would not be undue.
