<HEAD>Poll Finds Voters Know Little of Bush, Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the presidential election nine weeks off, sizable numbers of likely voters say they do n't know much about the candidates and feel the contenders are avoiding the issues, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. A poll conducted for the magazine last week found improvement in Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s ratings for trustworthiness and reliability and declines for Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in terms of trustworthiness and experience. Overall, 47 percent of the 1,103 likely voters nationwide favored <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, to 42 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The margin of error was three points, meaning the race statistically was a dead heat. That result was among voters who are registered and considered likely to vote. Among all registered voters _ 1,474 of them in the poll _ the race was even tighter: 44 percent for the Republicans, 42 percent for the Democrats. Time's survey, conducted Thursday and Friday, found that public opinion remained largely unformed about the candidates as the campaign enters its final stretch, and large swings in support remained possible. A fifth of the likely voters backing each ticket said they might change their minds. Fully 50 percent of the likely voters said they knew `` not much at all'' about <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and what kind of president he would be, and 29 percent said that about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, despite <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s nearly eight-year tenure as vice president. About half the likely voters said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was `` avoiding the real issues,'' and nearly as many, 44 percent, said that of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who caught up in the polls with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> after the Republican convention last month, was rated favorably by 58 percent of the likely voters, compared to a 49 percent favorable rating for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Each of the men was rated unfavorably by a third of the likely voters. Moreover, 58 percent rated <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as `` someone you can trust,'' up from 48 percent in a Time poll in April, and 60 percent said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could handle an international crisis, up from 51 percent in April. Fifty-three percent rated <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as trustworthy, down from 61 percent in April, and 43 percent said he has the experience to be president, down from 53 percent in April. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was rated far better on experience _ 83 percent _ and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was viewed as reliable in a crisis by just 40 percent. However, 72 percent said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> cares about average Americans; 57 percent said so of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Forty percent in the survey rated <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as `` too liberal,'' indicating that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s attacks on ideological grounds have had some effect. But while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has tied himself to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s record, 51 percent in the poll said they wanted the next president to `` follow different policies,'' to 42 percent who favored continuing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s policies
