<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As any casual follower of the stock market knows, a lot of the market's recent woes have been blamed on rising interest rates. But it is the way rates have been rising, even more than the simple fact that they have been moving up, that particularly troubles some analysts. With several nudges from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, short-term interest rates -LRB- on debt securities with lives of a year or less -RRB- have climbed more sharply of late than long-term rates -LRB- on bonds with maturities of up to 30 years -RRB-. That means that what Wall Streeters call the yield curve, a graphic representation of the relationship between short - and long-term rates, is flattening If it inverts _ that is, if short-term rates go higher than long-term rates _ many analysts believe it would be a sign of significant trouble for both the stock market and the economy. Normally, interest rates on long-term debt tend to be higher than on short-term loans because long-term borrowers expose themselves to greater risk that the purchasing power of their money will be eroded by inflation, or that the issuer of the debt will default. So when the yield curve tilts in the opposite direction, it is widely taken as a sign that something is out of whack. Inverted yield curves showed up early in the bear markets and recessions that occurred in 1973-74 and again at the beginning of the 1980s. `` If the yield curve inverts, there is a very high probability that a recession will follow,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Berge </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Tucker </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anthony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; R.L. <ORGANIZATION> Day </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, in a recent commentary. Recently, she noted, the ratio of rates on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills to those on 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds stood at .78. `` If the ratio rises above .80 and the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> does not cut the discount rate, historical probability indicates that the yield curve will invert,'' she said. Another cause for concern, in the view of <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorrentino </PERSON>, technical analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, is the fact that rates on three-month T-bills, at more than 7 percent, are higher than the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s discount rate, which it recently raised from 6 percent to 6.5 percent. `` Such a positive spread is a sign of a restrictive <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> policy, which usually places downward pressure on the stock market,'' <PERSON> Sorrentino </PERSON> said. `` Until the T-bill rate falls below the discount rate, this measure will remain in a bearish mode.'' Analysts at the financial advisory service <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s Moneyletter say managers of money market mutual funds have also been sounding a warning about interest rates and the financial outlook in recent months As a group, these managers have been shortening the average maturities of the securities in their portfolios. The standard motive for shortening maturities is to avoid or minimize price declines for existing securities when interest rates rise, and to have money available soon to invest at higher rates. `` When these managers believe interest rates are poised for a rise, they invest their funds in shorter-term securities,'' the newsletter said. `` Since the shortening began, the stock market generally has been moving sideways, and it recently has declined in the face of higher interest rates.''
</TEXT>
